<h1 class="hero-h">How to Document Your AI Workflows <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">Make AI rollout durable beyond the AI lead.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">The most common single point of failure in AI rollouts: all the working knowledge lives in one person's head. They leave, the rollout collapses. Documenting your AI workflows takes 1-2 hours per workflow and pays back enormously. Here's the structure that works.</p>
<div class="tldr"><div class="tldr-l">Short answer</div><p class="tldr-p">Each AI workflow should have a 1-page doc covering: purpose, owner, the Project setup (prompt + knowledge + inputs), the human review checkpoint, the success metric, and the last-reviewed date. Store in your shared knowledge base. Update when the workflow changes.</p></div>
</div></div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">Why documentation matters more for AI workflows than other workflows</h2><ul class="ul"><li>Prompts are subtle. Without documentation, the next person can't understand why the prompt is structured that way.</li><li>Project knowledge is consequential. Without documentation, no one knows what's loaded or why.</li><li>AI workflows evolve. Without docs, the team loses the why behind each iteration.</li><li>Departures wipe out tribal knowledge fast. AI lead leaves; rollout dies.</li><li>Auditors and customers increasingly ask. "How do you use AI?" needs a credible answer.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">The one-page workflow doc structure</h2><ol class="ol"><li><strong>Workflow name and one-sentence purpose.</strong></li><li><strong>Owner.</strong> Named human, with backup named.</li><li><strong>When to use it.</strong> Specific trigger.</li><li><strong>The Project setup.</strong> Where it lives, what knowledge is loaded, the system prompt.</li><li><strong>The inputs.</strong> What the user pastes in.</li><li><strong>The output.</strong> What good output looks like (with a sample).</li><li><strong>The human review checkpoint.</strong> Who reviews, what they check, before output ships.</li><li><strong>The success metric.</strong> How we know this is working.</li><li><strong>Last reviewed:</strong> date.</li><li><strong>Change log.</strong> What's changed since version 1, briefly.</li></ol></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">Where to store it</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Notion / Coda / Confluence:</strong> good for most teams. Searchable, structured.</li><li><strong>A shared folder of markdown files in your repo:</strong> good for engineering-heavy teams.</li><li><strong>Avoid:</strong> personal docs, Slack threads, individual Drives. The point is shared access.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">Governance</h2><ol class="ol"><li>Every new workflow gets a doc before it ships to the team. No exceptions.</li><li>Quarterly review: AI lead reads all workflow docs, updates Last Reviewed date or marks for revision.</li><li>Workflows without owners or recent reviews get sunset.</li><li>New AI hires read the workflow docs as part of onboarding.</li><li>Workflow docs are shareable with auditors, customers, or new exec hires when they ask how you use AI.</li></ol></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">Anti-patterns</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>30-page workflow specs.</strong> Nobody reads them. Stick to one page.</li><li><strong>Documentation that lives in the AI lead's personal Notion.</strong> Move to the shared space.</li><li><strong>'Living docs' that nobody updates.</strong> Set a quarterly review cadence.</li><li><strong>Including the Project's loaded knowledge in the doc.</strong> Link to it; don't duplicate.</li><li><strong>Documentation as the goal.</strong> The goal is the workflow shipping value; docs are insurance for continuity.</li></ul></div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">FAQ</h2>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">How often should I update workflow docs?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Update when the workflow changes (new prompt, new knowledge). Review quarterly for staleness.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Who owns updating workflow docs?</h3><p class="faq-qa">The workflow owner. Not the AI lead — that creates a bottleneck.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Should the documentation include the actual prompts?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Yes. Prompts are the workflow.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">What if our team has 30 workflows? That's 30 docs.</h3><p class="faq-qa">Yes. Each is one page. Pays back many times over.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Should we share these docs externally?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Generally no — they encode your competitive workflow knowledge. Share excerpts on request (auditors, customers).</p></div>
</div></section>

